{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"duration_ms":109567,"duration_api_ms":109180,"num_turns":6,"result":"","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"11c3ff00-8b38-4c60-a3aa-7cfa99520bd1","total_cost_usd":0.4265634,"usage":{"input_tokens":7,"cache_creation_input_tokens":30375,"cache_read_input_tokens":201641,"output_tokens":2260,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":30375,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"},"modelUsage":{"claude-opus-4-6":{"inputTokens":7,"outputTokens":2260,"cacheReadInputTokens":201641,"cacheCreationInputTokens":30375,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.34719924999999996,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":64000},"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001":{"inputTokens":17,"outputTokens":7032,"cacheReadInputTokens":41434,"cacheCreationInputTokens":32035,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.07936415,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":32000}},"permission_denials":[],"structured_output":{"summary":"Reviewed 7 amendments concerning legacy runless task-run handling. The amendments range from spec-compliance documentation gaps, missing tests, timestamp correctness issues, I/O atomicity bugs, to incomplete migration of timestamp-based identity heuristics. Most amendments identify real defects or important gaps that should be addressed, though some have lower severity than others.","votes":[{"amendment_id":"fr-21-e7e21072","decision":"accept","rationale":"The amendment correctly identifies that unique_terminal_replay_match, is_legacy_start_for, and is_superseded_legacy_start remain in active code paths despite the spec requiring their removal. The fail_legacy_runless_entries migration was a pragmatic compromise, but the spec deviation is undocumented. The ask is reasonable: either complete the removal or formally document the retained backward-compat paths with rationale. Undocumented deviations from spec create confusion for future maintainers and risk the assumption that these paths are dead code when they are not."},{"amendment_id":"fr-21-c3d756b1","decision":"accept","rationale":"fail_legacy_runless_entries mutates on-disk state and is invoked on every record_task_run_start and update_task_run call. The spec requires test coverage for each fix. The three proposed test scenarios are well-scoped and directly relevant: (1) verify legacy entries get failed with correct outcome_detail, (2) verify terminal entries are untouched, (3) verify new runs proceed after repair. This is a critical migration function that modifies persistent state — testing it is essential, not optional."},{"amendment_id":"fr-21-93ff22d8","decision":"accept","rationale":"The timestamp issue is real. fail_legacy_runless_entries receives the caller's timestamp (started_at or finished_at) and uses it as finished_at for legacy entries. If a legacy entry's started_at is later than the caller's timestamp (clock skew, out-of-order writes), this creates finished_at < started_at — an impossible timeline that could confuse any downstream logic inspecting durations or chronological ordering. Using max(legacy_entry.started_at, now) is a straightforward defensive fix with no downside."},{"amendment_id":"fr-21-fa9403b6","decision":"accept","rationale":"The double-write issue is real but moderate severity. Both record_task_run_start and update_task_run write entries immediately when legacy repair triggers, then may write again at the end. This creates: (1) unnecessary I/O on every call that encounters legacy data, (2) a brief window where on-disk state has legacy repairs but not the actual operation. Folding legacy repair into the final write path is cleaner and avoids the partial-state window. This is also directly related to amendment fr-21-97db243d — if the repair is deferred to the final write, both the atomicity and double-write issues are resolved together."},{"amendment_id":"fr-21-56323054","decision":"accept","rationale":"The same_attempt fallback to started_at matching when either run_id is None is a latent correctness risk. After fail_legacy_runless_entries marks all runless Running entries as terminal, live (non-terminal) entries should always have run_id. However, this invariant is implicit — nothing enforces or documents it. A debug_assert!(left.run_id.is_some() && right.run_id.is_some()) on the non-terminal path, or at minimum a comment explaining when the fallback is still needed, would make the invariant explicit and catch violations early. This is a low-cost, high-value defensive measure."},{"amendment_id":"fr-21-97db243d","decision":"accept","rationale":"This is the most serious amendment. The legacy repair write at lines 2818-2822 and 2943-2947 happens before validation checks. If a later check fails (duplicate-finalized, missing/ambiguous update), the function returns an error, but task-runs.ndjson has already been mutated. The service layer's snapshot/journal reconciliation at service.rs:439-452 and 568-584 only runs after the adapter succeeds. This leaves task-runs.ndjson in a state inconsistent with status.json and journal.ndjson. Delaying the legacy repair write until the operation is confirmed to succeed (or surfacing it through the service layer for coordinated writes) is necessary to maintain cross-artifact consistency."},{"amendment_id":"fr-21-fc1d9825","decision":"accept","rationale":"The amendment correctly identifies that the read path still uses timestamp-based identity heuristics for runless entries via unique_open_legacy_group_index and legacy_group_accepts_completion. These feed collapse_task_run_attempts, which is used by snapshot reconciliation and bead audit queries. A legacy/corrupt runless row sharing a timestamp with a different named run can be folded into the wrong canonical attempt. While fail_legacy_runless_entries mitigates this for write paths by failing runless Running entries, existing terminal runless entries (legitimately completed legacy entries) still flow through this timestamp-based grouping. The remove-runless-matching change is indeed incomplete on the read side."}]},"fast_mode_state":"off","uuid":"335202d3-2ee2-4fb1-9ff6-956ac2657006"}
